Platform: OS X
Language: Python 2.7

Source code submitted by: Casey Currey-Wilson (cs184-ap)
Located at: /~cs184-ap/ass4/
Primary source file is: kinematics.py

Required to run:
	NumPy - http://www.numpy.org/
	PyGame - http://www.pygame.org/
	PyOpenGL - http://pyopengl.sourceforge.net/

Assignment web page:
http://inst.cs.berkeley.edu/~cs184-ap/ass4.html


Program does not need to be compiled. Because Python.

Run using "python kinematics.py" followed by the x, y and z values of the initial goal point, followed by the lengths of each segment.
	Example: "python kinematics.py 1 2 0 2 0.8 4 2.3 1 .7"

Outside sources used:
CS184 Lecture Slides from Professor O'Brien
Peter Shirley and Steve Marschner's Fundamentals of Computer Graphics
Parametric equation of a circle - http://math.stackexchange.com/questions/73237/parametric-equation-of-a-circle-in-3d-space
PyOpenGL - http://pyopengl.sourceforge.net/
Pygame - http://www.pygame.org/
NumPy - http://www.numpy.org/
Inverse Kinematics in Python - https://studywolf.wordpress.com/2013/04/11/inverse-kinematics-of-3-link-arm-with-constrained-minimization-in-python/
Jacobian in NumPy - http://www.quantstart.com/articles/Jacobi-Method-in-Python-and-NumPy